                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d523">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.12155/428: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Mexico</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Lowry</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Mexico</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-05-31T12:00:00-06:00"
                            >May 31, 1930—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 5:19 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>109. Reference Department’s telegram 144, dated May 29, 1 p.m. Having in mind the
                    existing uncertainties as to Cabinet personnel already reported to the
                    Department and that the suggested exchange of notes would at best be merely an
                    agreement to make an agreement, we suggest that probably the wiser course would
                    be to go forward under the Mexican Government’s proposal contained in its note
                    of May 28 [<hi rend="italic">27</hi>], 1930, transmitted with despatch 2495 of
                    May 29.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lowry</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
